<font color="#FF0000">THANKS... AND KEEP WRITING</font><br>
<tt>Sun Mar 16 19:27:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
TO ALL WHO READ AND CONTRIBUTED TO THIS SITE....<br><br>
Our Viet Nam seminar finished last Thursday night with 18 outstanding student presentations. In my concluding comments to the participants and to the guests who attended, I stated that I didn't know who learned more: the first and second year students, the guest speakers, or myself. Viet Nam continues to haunt us. I can say the following, that we learned enough to say that we are at the &quot;end of the beginning,&quot; and that the students and I will continue our voyage of discovery into the years that follow. <br><br>
During the course of the 10 week quarter we experienced a broad range of emotions, from joy to sorrow; from delight to frustration; from quiet appreciation to rage; from anger to compassion. <br><br>
Participants heard from veterans and civilians, caught up in activities that ranged from combat to anti-war activities; from work in Viet Nam to efforts conducted in America; from prisoners of war; from the tortured as well as from men and women who have made their peace with events of the 1960's - 1970's.  <br><br>
Participants helped when the replica of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington D.C. came to Capital Park in Sacramento. They worked with mothers-fathers, wives-husbands, children-relatives-friends to find the names of their loved ones on the pannels. <br><br>
Participants met with veterans at the California Vietnam Veterans Memorial for an evening of remembering and contemplation.<br><br>
Participants investigated the 1968 Tet Offensive and concluded that the media DID influence the American withdrawl and ultimately the fall of South Viet Nam. But whether the media influence was positive or negative was determined by a range of other issues, not the least of which was whether or not additional lives were saved by American withdrawl in 1973. <br><br>
Participants studied the literature, poetry, and music of the era. And when the song clips were played on that last seminar evening, memories once held inside were released, as a new generation of students understood the meaning and symbolism of the words coined by Pete Seager, Bob Dylan, the Weavers, Country Joe McDonald and the Fish, and a host of others.....<br><br>
The student individual and team reports are due this next Friday. The overall plan is to place these documents on the web. How and when all this will take place needs considerable thinking, but I would hope that we could be completed with all the &quot;details&quot; before summer.<br><br>
Some of you I promised to send you copies of our course materials. Like so many promises this quarter, these were good intentions, but I do have a stack of mail to send out now that the quarter crisis is easing, so those of you who have waited.... &quot;its in the mail.&quot;<br><br>
I would hope, too, that those of you who participated in the PBS/POV national dialog on Viet Nam (where Toni and I worked together), that you would continue to add points to this dialog site.<br><br>
Best of all, I want to thank all of you who so kindly answered my student's questions, who replied -- even when one of the questions was worded in a &quot;curious&quot; way.<br><br>
As I wrote to John in the previous post, I am working on a detailed chronology of the war years, and will be spending much of my summer getting through the New York Times annual index. <br><br>
IF ANYBODY KNOWS OF A DETAILED CHRONOLOGY OF THE VIET NAM WAR, PLEASE LET ME KNOW. I AM USING INFORMATION AVAILABLE FROM THE FOLLOWING:<br><br>
The Vietnam War Day by Day. Editor. John Bowman. Hong <br>
Kong: Mallard Press, 1989; and<br><br>
Cooper, Chester L. The lost crusade; America in Vietnam, <br>
by Chester L. Cooper. With a foreword by W. Averell <br>
Harriman.  New York, Dodd, Mead, 1970.<br><br>
Still, I find these with lots of &quot;gaps.&quot;<br><br>
We also are working on war-related quotations that seem to express the issues, confusion, and difficulties of Viet Nam; we are up to 12 pages..... will post if anybody is interested.<br><br>
Regards.<br><br>

